Introduction

In the expansive and dynamic realm of music streaming platforms, exploring the characteristics of songs opens up opportunities for profound insights that can transform user experiences. Within the extensive array of tracks available on platforms like Spotify, the ability to identify patterns and connections among diverse audio attributes holds tremendous potential. This analysis sets out on a voyage through the intricate landscape of audio features, encompassing various genres, with the objective of predicting song popularity, crafting personalized playlists, and enriching overall user satisfaction.

In our quest, we will dive into the detailed elements of songs, employing robust machine learning models such as k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Random Forest, XGBoost, and others. By scrutinizing the distributions of audio features and revealing correlations between them, our aim is to unravel the inherent patterns that define genres and captivate audiences. These models not only hold the capability to predict a song’s genre but also offer a nuanced comprehension of how diverse audio attributes contribute to its allure.

Moreover, our exploration extends into the realm of danceability, a fundamental aspect of music that often transcends genre boundaries. To grasp the influence of different features on danceability, we utilize methodologies such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and regression analysis. These techniques enable us to distill the essential components that shape a song’s danceability, providing insights into the intricate interplay of harmonies, rhythms, and melodies.

As we embark on this analytical journey, our goal is to uncover the concealed intricacies within the fabric of musical compositions. By decoding the complex relationships between audio features, genres, and danceability, we strive to offer not just predictive insights but also a heightened appreciation for the artistry that defines our diverse and constantly evolving musical landscape.

Dataset

The real-time dataset same as the one used in midterm, encompasses a comprehensive collection of 42,305 rows, merging information from Spotify’s vast music library. The dataset presents a rich assortment of information, combining various audio features and metadata related to diverse musical tracks, offering a nuanced perspective on the intricate characteristics of contemporary music.

The dataset comprises an array of audio features, including danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence, tempo, and time signature. These features provide valuable insights into the nuanced musical compositions and inherent attributes of each track, enabling a deeper understanding of the multifaceted nature of musical expression and creativity.

Additionally, the dataset incorporates a range of unique identifiers, such as type, id, URI, track_href, and analysis_url, facilitating seamless linkage and retrieval of supplementary information associated with each track. This interconnected system offers an expansive view of the diverse musical landscape, highlighting the interconnected nature of contemporary music production and distribution.

Furthermore, the dataset includes critical information on the duration of each track, meticulously measured in milliseconds, and encompasses genre classifications, specific song names, and titles of individual tracks. This comprehensive dataset serves as a valuable resource for conducting in-depth analyses and uncovering intricate patterns and trends within the dynamic realm of music composition and production.

Key Columns:

Danceability: Signifies the track’s suitability for dancing, incorporating a blend of musical elements to gauge its rhythmic and dance-friendly nature.

Energy: Represents the song’s intensity and activity level, encapsulating features such as tempo, volume, and rhythmic strength to define the overall dynamism and liveliness of the music.

Key: Reflects the musical key of the track, determining the pitch and tonality of the music and contributing to the overall melodic structure and tonal composition. Loudness: Indicates the overall volume or amplitude of the song, measured in decibels (dB), offering insights into the track’s auditory presence and sonic impact.

Mode: Represents the modality (major or minor) of a track, delineating the type of scale used in the track’s melodic construction and serving as a foundational element in defining the music’s emotional tone and tonal texture.

Speechiness: Indicates the presence of spoken words in the song, helping to distinguish between instrumental and vocal-centric compositions.

Acousticness: Represents the presence of acoustic elements in the song, with high values suggesting a stronger presence of acoustic sounds.

Instrumentalness: Reflects the probability of a track being instrumental, with higher values indicating a higher likelihood of the absence of vocals.

Liveness: Indicates the likelihood of a track being recorded live, highlighting the presence of an audience or live recording ambiance.

Valence: Represents the overall mood and emotional character of a track, typically denoting the positivity or happiness conveyed by the music.

Tempo: Indicates the speed or pace of a track, typically measured in beats per minute (BPM), defining the overall rhythm and pacing of the music.

Duration_ms: Represents the duration of the track in milliseconds, providing insights into the length and temporal structure of the music.

Genre: Indicates the genre or category to which the song belongs, defining its stylistic and thematic classification within the broader spectrum of music.

Song_name: Refers to the name or title of the individual song, serving as a distinctive identifier for each musical composition.

Title: Represents the title of the track or the name of the musical composition, providing a unique identifier for cataloging and organizational purposes.

Time_Signature: Indicates the notational convention specifying the number of beats in each bar or measure, providing insights into the rhythmic structure and temporal organization of the music.

These key columns collectively contribute to a comprehensive understanding of the musical attributes, thematic characteristics, and genre-specific classifications within the Spotify dataset.

There are certain limitations as well in the dataset.The dataset from Spotify provides valuable insights into music characteristics and genre trends, yet it comes with certain limitations that warrant attention. One primary concern revolves around potential biases in the sampled data, which might not fully represent the rich diversity of musical genres and styles. Moreover, the dataset’s static nature could restrict a comprehensive understanding of dynamic shifts in music trends over time. Additionally, the absence of detailed metadata and potential data quality issues, such as missing or inaccurate values, pose challenges to the reliability and robustness of any analytical inferences drawn from the dataset. It is imperative to acknowledge these limitations to ensure a balanced and nuanced interpretation of the dataset’s findings within the broader context of music analysis and industry insights.

Source of dataset: This research project’s dataset (Dataset of songs in Spotify)was obtained via Kaggle, a recognized site for sharing and accessing datasets.[1]

Exploratory Data Analysis

In the scholarly realm of data analysis, Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) stands as a pivotal phase, akin to the preliminary investigations conducted by a seasoned researcher before embarking on a comprehensive study. Picture this phase as the initial survey of an unexplored scientific landscape, where the analyst endeavors to unearth latent patterns, identify anomalies, test hypotheses, and validate assumptions through a meticulous examination of summary statistics and graphical representations.

Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) refers to the critical process of performing initial investigations on data so as to discover patterns,to spot anomalies,to test hypothesis and to check assumptions with the help of summary statistics and graphical representations.[2]

The main purpose of EDA is to help look at data before making any assumptions. It can help identify obvious errors, as well as better understand patterns within the data, detect outliers or anomalous events, find interesting relations among the variables.[3]

Graphical representations, the visual lexicon of academia, play a crucial role in this narrative. Histograms, scatter plots, and box plots are akin to visual arguments, illustrating relationships between variables and conveying complex concepts with clarity. These visual aids not only facilitate the analyst’s understanding but also serve as communicative tools in scholarly discourse.

Moreover, EDA validates assumptions, a process analogous to literature review and theoretical grounding in academic research. It ensures that the initial assumptions made about the dataset withstand scholarly scrutiny, providing a robust foundation for subsequent analyses.

Visulaization of Data

Data visualization is an important component of Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) because it allows a data analyst to “look at” their data and get to know the variables and relationships between them.[4]

Previously in our midterm we focussed our EDA on induvidual features and as well as the some of the bivariate analysis, but this time let us consider the summary of the univariate analysis and proceed further with newer set plots and analysis.

Reiterating that Univariate analysis focuses on a single variable at a time. Box plots (or violin plots) and histograms are common choices for visually summarizing a quantitative variable. These plots are useful because they simultaneously communicate information about minimum and maximum values, central location, and spread. Histograms can additionally illuminate patterns that can impact an analysis.[4]

The previously visualized graphs and analyses in midterm provide a comprehensive insight into the audio features within the dataset. Regarding danceability, a noteworthy proportion of songs seem suitable for dancing, particularly peaking between 0.7 and 0.8. Energy levels display a bimodal distribution, encompassing both moderately and highly energetic tracks. Consistent loudness values suggest a standardized approach to mastering in production. Speechiness values indicate a preference for instrumental content, with some tracks, especially those in the 0.33 to 0.66 range, incorporating speech elements for added diversity. Acousticness generally remains low, with a prominent peak near 1, indicating a subset of purely acoustic tracks. Instrumentalness values reflect the prevalence of vocal presence but also emphasize purely instrumental compositions. Liveness values predominantly signify studio recordings, occasionally featuring high values for live performances. Valence values exhibit a scattered distribution, showcasing emotional and thematic diversity. Tempo and duration fall within common ranges for mainstream music. Categorical variables further enhance the analysis, highlighting the uniform distribution of musical keys, prevalence of major scale modes, diverse genre representations (with “Underground Rap” being notable), and the dominance of the “4” time signature, indicating rhythmic consistency. Overall, these findings present a nuanced depiction of the dataset’s musical characteristics, capturing both shared elements and the diverse richness evident in the analyzed audio features.

By examining the interactions and associations between these variables, analysts can uncover valuable insights into how changes in one variable might impact the other. This form of analysis allows for the identification of patterns, trends, and correlations that might exist between the two variables, providing a comprehensive understanding of their interdependence. mode_genre_distribution <- dataset_na %>%
  group_by(genre, mode) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = mode, values_from = count, values_fill = list(count = 0))

# Converting 'mode' columns to factor for better labeling in the plot
mode_genre_distribution$`0` <- as.factor(mode_genre_distribution$`0`)
mode_genre_distribution$`1` <- as.factor(mode_genre_distribution$`1`)



p4 <- ggplot(mode_genre_distribution, aes(x = genre, y = `1`, fill = "Major")) +

Relationship between Tempo and Energy across Genres:

Correlation between Tempo and Energy: There does not appear to be a clear, consistent correlation between faster tempos and higher energy across all genres. While some genres may show this trend, it’s not a universal rule applicable to all.

Genre-Specific Patterns: The relationship between tempo and energy varies significantly by genre. Some genres, possibly like electronic or dance music, might show a trend where higher tempo correlates with higher energy. In contrast, other genres, such as classical or jazz, might not exhibit such a strong correlation, having both high-energy fast tracks and low-energy fast tracks.

Diverse Energy Levels at Similar Tempos: At any given tempo, there’s a wide range of energy levels. This suggests that tempo alone doesn’t dictate the energy level of a track, and other factors like instrumentation, rhythm complexity, and production techniques also play significant roles.

High Tempo Doesn’t Always Mean High Energy: There are numerous points in the higher tempo range (say above 140 BPM) that do not correspond to high energy levels. This indicates that fast songs are not always energetic.

Clusters and Overlaps: Some genres may cluster together, showing similar tempo-energy characteristics, while others overlap significantly, indicating shared attributes across genres.

Outliers: Any outliers on the plot (e.g., very high-energy tracks at lower tempos or vice versa) could be particularly interesting for further analysis, as they defy the common trends observed.

In conclusion, while there might be a general tendency for faster songs to be more energetic in certain genres, this plot demonstrates that it’s not a universal rule across all genres. The relationship between tempo and energy is complex and influenced by genre-specific characteristics.

Relationship between Speechiness and Liveness across Genres:

General Distribution: The majority of tracks, regardless of genre, tend to have low speechiness and liveness levels. This suggests that instrumental music or tracks with limited spoken words are more common, and most tracks are studio-recorded rather than live recordings.

Concentration of Points: Most genres seem to cluster in the lower left corner of the plot (low speechiness and low liveness), indicating that tracks with high levels of speechiness or liveness are less common.

High Speechiness and Liveness: There are few tracks with both high speechiness and high liveness. This might represent specific genres like live rap or spoken word performances where spoken content is predominant in a live setting.

Genre Variation: Some genres might show a tendency towards higher speechiness or liveness, but the plot does not clearly segregate genres based on these two features. This indicates that speechiness and liveness alone might not be strong distinguishing factors for genres.

Sparse High Liveness: Tracks with higher liveness (towards the top of the plot) are relatively sparse, suggesting that live recordings or tracks with audience interaction are less frequent in the dataset.

Outliers: There are some outliers, particularly in terms of high speechiness. These tracks could be interesting to explore further, as they might represent genres or styles that heavily focus on spoken words, like hip-hop, rap, or certain types of electronic music.

Lack of Strong Correlation: There is no clear pattern or strong correlation suggesting that higher speechiness consistently leads to higher liveness or vice versa. This might imply that the presence of spoken words in a track does not necessarily mean the track is a live recording.

These observations provide an overview of how speechiness and liveness characteristics are distributed across different genres. However, the specific insights and interpretations could vary depending on the details and nuances of the dataset.

Distribution of Tempo across Genres:

The boxplot above illustrates the distribution of tempo (measured in Beats Per Minute, BPM) across different music genres. Here are some observations from the plot:

Variability in Tempo: Each genre has a unique distribution of tempo, with some genres showing a wider range of tempos than others. This reflects the rhythmic diversity present within each genre.

Median Tempo: The median tempo (indicated by the line in the middle of each box) varies significantly across genres. Some genres have higher median tempos, suggesting a generally faster pace, while others have lower median tempos.

Outliers: The presence of outliers (indicated by dots outside the boxes) in several genres suggests that there are songs with tempos that are significantly different from the majority in that genre. These could represent sub-genres or experimental tracks that deviate from the norm.

Interquartile Range (IQR): The height of each box (representing the IQR) shows the spread of the middle 50% of the data. A taller box implies greater variability in tempo within that genre.

Comparisons Between Genres: Some genres have overlapping IQRs, indicating similarities in tempo range, while others are distinctly separate, indicating unique tempo characteristics.

Genre-Specific Characteristics: The plot allows for the identification of genre-specific tempo characteristics. For example, some electronic or dance-oriented genres might show consistently higher tempos, while genres like jazz or classical might have a broader range of tempos.

This visualization is effective for comparing tempo distributions across genres and identifying unique tempo-related characteristics inherent to specific styles of music.

Relationship between Danceability and Valence :

General Trend: There doesn’t appear to be a strong, consistent linear correlation between danceability and valence. While there are a significant number of tracks that are both highly danceable and have high valence, there are also many tracks with high danceability and low valence.

Variability Across the Spectrum: Both danceability and valence exhibit a wide range of values, indicating a diverse set of tracks in terms of their musical and emotional characteristics.

Clusters of Tracks: There are clusters of tracks with high danceability and high valence, which might indicate genres or styles that are both upbeat and danceable. Similarly, there are clusters with high danceability but lower valence.

No Clear Genre Segregation: Without color-coding by genre, it’s challenging to discern clear genre-specific patterns from this plot alone. The distribution of points suggests that both danceable and emotionally positive traits are not confined to specific genres.

Spread of Danceability: Danceability seems to be more uniformly spread compared to valence, which has a more varied distribution.

This analysis suggests that while danceable music often tends to be more positive, this is not a rule, and there is considerable variability in the emotional tone of danceable tracks.

Danceability holds paramount importance in the realm of music as it serves as a gateway to a rich tapestry of experiences. More than a mere metric, danceability reflects a song’s capacity to inspire physical movement, transforming the act of listening into a dynamic and participatory engagement. Beyond personal enjoyment, danceability fosters social connections, acting as a catalyst for communal celebrations and shared moments on dance floors. Additionally, danceability intersects with health and well-being, as it often accompanies fitness activities, making physical exertion more enjoyable.

So now coming to our first SMART question-

1) How do specific music features such as energy, loudness, speechiness, etc contribute to the perceived danceability of a song, and can we uncover latent patterns within these features that significantly impact danceability?

Let us divide this question into 2 parts-

  1. How do individual music features contribute to the perceived danceability of a song?
  2. Can we uncover latent patterns within these features that significantly impact danceability and How accurately can these features predict danceability using a regression model?

Next let us try to focus on the second part of the SMART question 1(b)-

We are going to be using the Principal Component Analysis followed by a regression model to answer this part of the question. To understand how specific music features contribute to the perceived danceability of a song and uncover latent patterns within these features, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and regression models can be valuable tools. Regression models, such as linear regression, can be employed to quantify the relationships between individual music features and danceability. By fitting a regression model with danceability as the dependent variable and energy, loudness, speechiness, and other relevant features as independent variables, one can estimate the impact and significance of each feature on danceability. After applying PCA, the principal components that emerge can be used as predictors in regression models.

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a technique frequently employed for diminishing the dimensionality of extensive data sets. This method involves transforming a substantial set of variables into a more compact one while retaining the majority of information from the original dataset. Although reducing variables inevitably leads to a loss of precision, the key in dimensionality reduction is to strike a balance, sacrificing some accuracy for the sake of simplicity. The advantage lies in the ease of exploration, visualization, and accelerated processing of data points for machine learning algorithms, as smaller datasets are more manageable and efficient without unnecessary variables.[5]

In this case, the first component explains 25.85% of the variance, and the second component explains 19.38% of the variance, with the cumulative percentage of variance increasing as we consider more components. This information is useful for determining the number of components to retain in the analysis. The variable contributions show how much each musical feature contributes to each principal component. To assess the predictive power of these features on danceability, regression models can be built using the principal components as predictors. The PCA results offer a comprehensive exploration of latent patterns in the data and provide a foundation for constructing regression models to predict danceability based on the identified principal components.As we are able to see that the principal components with the highest contributions to danceability are “Dim.1” followed by “Dim.3.” and so on. “Dim.1” and “Dim.3” refer to the principal components themselves, each representing a linear combination of the original variables (in this case, musical features) in the dataset. These components are derived in such a way that they capture the maximum variance in the data.

linear_model <- lm(danceability ~ Dim.1 + Dim.2 + Dim.3 + Dim.4 + Dim.5, data = train_data)

predictions <- predict(linear_model, newdata = test_data)

Next we have our Final SMART question-

3) How accurate are models in predicting the genre of songs in the dataset based on the given features?

To answer this question we have chosen these 4 models with their reason for use and their nature mentioned-

RandomForest:

Nature: Random Forest stands out as a popular machine learning algorithm created by Leo Breiman and Adele Cutler. It is an ensemble learning method based on decision tree algorithms. It operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees during training and outputting the mode of the classes (classification) of the individual trees.[6]

Why Chosen: It’s known for its robustness and ability to handle large datasets with a mix of numerical and categorical features. RandomForest is effective in reducing overfitting by averaging the results of individual trees, thereby improving generalization. It’s also good at handling missing data and maintains accuracy even when a significant proportion of the data is missing.

Gradient Boosting:

Nature: Gradient Boosting is another ensemble technique that builds trees sequentially, with each tree trying to correct the errors made by the previous ones.Basically it is a powerful boosting algorithm that combines several weak learners into strong learners, in which each new model is trained to minimize the loss function such as mean squared error or cross-entropy of the previous model using gradient descent.[7]

Why Chosen: It’s highly effective in classification tasks due to its ability to minimize both bias and variance, leading to more accurate models. It’s particularly useful in scenarios where the relationship between features and target variable is complex and non-linear. The model’s flexibility allows it to capture intricate patterns in the data.

XGBoost:

Nature: XGBoost, which stands for Extreme Gradient Boosting, is a scalable, distributed gradient-boosted decision tree (GBDT) machine learning library. It provides parallel tree boosting and is the leading machine learning library for regression, classification, and ranking problems.[8]

Why Chosen: XGBoost provides a highly efficient implementation of the gradient boosting algorithm. It’s not only faster but also has built-in mechanisms for handling missing data. Additionally, XGBoost includes regularization, which helps to prevent overfitting and can lead to better performance on unseen data. It’s particularly popular due to its speed and performance.

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN):

Nature: The k-nearest neighbors algorithm, also known as KNN or k-NN, is a non-parametric, supervised learning classifier, which uses proximity to make classifications or predictions about the grouping of an individual data point.[9]

Why Chosen: KNN was chosen as a contrasting approach to ensemble methods. It’s a straightforward and intuitive algorithm that works well when the dataset has a number of instances where similar cases are near each other in the feature space. It was included to see if a simpler approach could effectively handle the genre classification task without the complexities of ensemble methods.

Each of these models brings a different approach to the table: RandomForest and Gradient Boosting for their ensemble-based robustness, XGBoost for its efficiency and performance, and KNN for its simplicity and intuitive operation. The combination of these models offers a well-rounded perspective on how various machine learning techniques perform on the genre classification task, providing insights into the complexity and challenges of the dataset.

Tempo:

Observation: The tempo of a song, measured in beats per minute (BPM), is the most influential feature in predicting its genre. Impact on Genre: Different genres tend to have characteristic tempos. For example, genres like techno or trance typically have a higher BPM, while genres like RnB or pop might have a slower tempo.

Duration_ms (Duration in milliseconds):

Observation: The length of the song is a significant predictor of its genre. Impact on Genre: Certain genres are known for their typical song lengths. For instance, genres like pop or radio-friendly tracks might have shorter durations, whereas genres like progressive or trance might feature longer tracks.

Danceability:

Observation: Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. Impact on Genre: Genres like electronic dance music (EDM) or pop are often high in danceability, whereas genres such as ambient or classical might have lower danceability scores.

Instrumentalness:

Observation: This feature predicts whether a track contains no vocals. The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. Impact on Genre: Genres like techno, ambient, or instrumental jazz often have high instrumentalness. In contrast, genres such as rap or pop typically have lower scores due to the prominent vocal content.

Loudness:

Observation: Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Impact on Genre: Genres like rock, metal, or EDM often have higher loudness levels, while acoustic or classical genres tend to be quieter.

Energy:

Observation: Energy represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. Impact on Genre: High-energy genres include rock, metal, and EDM. In contrast, genres like jazz, classical, or RnB might exhibit lower energy levels.

Valence:

Observation: Valence measures the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. High valence sounds more positive (e.g., happy, cheerful, euphoric), while low valence sounds more negative (e.g., sad, depressed, angry). Impact on Genre: Genres like pop or certain strands of electronic music often have high valence, reflecting their generally upbeat nature. In contrast, genres like blues or some forms of metal might have lower valence, reflecting more somber or aggressive themes.

In summary, various musical features hold distinct significance in predicting genre. Tempo and duration shape the structural characteristics of a song, while danceability, instrumentalness, loudness, energy, and valence contribute to the emotional and stylistic aspects. Each feature illuminates specific traits that align with certain genres, underscoring the multifaceted nature of genre prediction based on musical attributes. Understanding the importance of these features provides valuable insights into the diverse musical landscape and the nuanced interplay between musical elements and genre classification.

We can summarize the results as follows-

Decreasing Train Deviance: The ‘TrainDeviance’ column shows a consistent decrease as the number of iterations (trees) increases. This indicates that the model is learning from the training data and becoming better at predicting the target variable ‘genre’ with each iteration.

Valid Deviance: The ‘ValidDeviance’ column shows -nan, which typically indicates missing or non-applicable values. This could happen if the validation set is not properly defined or if there’s an issue in the calculation of validation deviance. Ideally, you would want this value to decrease similarly to the Train Deviance to ensure the model is generalizing well and not overfitting.

Step Size (Learning Rate): The learning rate is constant at 0.1. This step size appears to be adequate, given the consistent improvement in training deviance without any indication of erratic jumps or divergence.

Improve: The ‘Improve’ column indicates the reduction in deviance with each iteration. Initially, the improvement is significant but gradually decreases, which is typical as the model starts to saturate in learning from the data. The decrease in improvement is more gradual, which is a good sign - it indicates that the learning rate and depth are well-tuned for this data.

Overfitting Concerns: Without the corresponding validation deviance, it’s challenging to comment on overfitting. Ideally, you’d want to see the validation deviance to ensure it’s in line with the training deviance.

Final Model Performance: By iteration 100, the improvement is close to zero or slightly negative, suggesting that adding more trees might not lead to better performance. This is a typical point to stop training in gradient boosting.

In summary, the model appears to be learning effectively from the training data. However, the lack of validation deviance data makes it difficult to evaluate the model’s generalization performance. The accuracy you provide later will be crucial to assess how well the model performs on unseen data.

dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(top_features_traindata[, -which(names(top_features_traindata) == "genre")]), label = top_features_traindata$genre)
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(top_features_testdata[, -which(names(test_data) == "genre")]), label = top_features_testdata$genre)


params <- list(
  booster = "gbtree",
  objective = "multi:softprob",  
  num_class = length(unique(top_features_traindata$genre)),
  eval_metric = "mlogloss"       
)

nrounds <- 100

xgb_model <- xgb.train(params = params, data = dtrain, nrounds = nrounds)
test_pred_prob <- predict(xgb_model, dtest)
num_class <- length(unique(top_features_traindata$genre))
test_pred <- matrix(test_pred_prob, ncol = num_class, byrow = TRUE)
test_pred_labels <- max.col(test_pred) - 1 


levels_genres <- levels(as.factor(top_features_traindata$genre))
test_pred_factor <- factor(test_pred_labels, levels = 0:(num_class - 1), labels = levels_genres)

conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(test_pred_factor, as.factor(top_features_testdata$genre))
accuracy <- conf_matrix$overall['Accuracy']
print(accuracy)

## 0.6606784

Overall Conclusion:

In evaluating the performance of various classification models for predicting music genres, a clear hierarchy emerges with Gradient Boosting leading the pack with the highest test accuracy at 66.27%, closely followed by XGBoost at 66.07%, and RandomForest trailing slightly behind at 65.06%. KNN, on the other hand, exhibits the lowest accuracy at 59.60%. The success of ensemble methods (RandomForest, Gradient Boosting, XGBoost) points to their prowess in handling intricate relationships within the data, either through constructing multiple decision trees or iteratively refining predictions. Conversely, KNN’s relatively poorer performance suggests that the genre classification task may involve complex patterns or lack well-defined boundaries within the feature space, hindering the algorithm’s efficacy. Overall, the ensemble methods exhibit superior suitability for the task, but the moderate performance across models suggests that the genre classification challenge remains intricate, requiring further exploration of features or modeling techniques.

This way, we contribute to the exciting and always changing world of discovering new music.
